messages.clean_content:
Formula for working out how many observer folds are needed for a flush piston extender of length *n*:

`ceiling([n-2]/3)`

Subtract 2 from *n*, divide by 3 and then round the number **up** to the nearest whole number. For example for a quintuple piston extender (5), subtract 2 from 5 (3), divide 3 by 3 (1), and round up to the nearest integer (1). You need 1 observer fold.

This formula also works for single and double piston extenders which **both return 0**.

after some more testing i figured out that relogging the game fully and going to the start menu is different from unloading and reloading the area. Due to this, this setup is relog proof because
- Game will place the trident on the left trident, then relog again and it will place it on the right trident, then the left trident etc.
- You don't need any blocks underneath, only that the trident is on the edge of the block
-Picture shows a setup so that no matter where the trident is located, it will power the piston above

messages.clean_content:
Black glass represents all of the possible placements for the hopper for trident update migration
- The decoy trident used(the not updated one) does not need any specific block to be on, just as long as it's within the range of the piston. Also not affected by gravity
- The way the hopper points to is where the fake piston points to, range is about as large as if a normal piston was facing sideways
- When the hopper faces down it has the same range as if a normal piston were to face down
- There are 10 possible spots to place the hopper, with 5 possible hopper pointing directions, and 6 possible piston directions, which totals to 300 total layouts for trident update migration

messages.clean_content:
So far, these are the laws of Trident update migration:
1. Piston and hopper must have direct contact with each other
2. Several pistons can connect to a hopper but not vice versa
3. The number of tridents the primary piston updates= The number of tridents the hopper updates
4. Secondary pistons must be updating a trident for the connection to work
5. If there are more than one hopper per piston, then a definitive update order will dictate which tridents will update first

messages.clean_content:
Bean Sand dust line input fix
Using a torch or repeater **when the observer is reading dust**, the top piston will fire 1 rt slower. Moving a block to power that line will fix it, but this presents a new problem which you can see in the video.
Giving the piston that has the sand block a 1 rt pulse will unfortunately not give enough time for the DPE to its thing. So to fix this, give a slightly longer pulse by double pulsing an observer or using a three tick repeater.

messages.clean_content:
Pressure Plate Unreliability:
The way a pressure plate works is that when you step on it, it will check whether you are still there or not every 10rt (5 for gold pressure plate)
Meaning if u step on it and get out right away, it will be same as if u step on it and get out like 5 rt after
So if u step out after a random amount of time, u will have to wait until the next check which may be after 0 or 3 or 6 rt
So that's why some builds with pressure plate are unreliable
But so the time between pressure plate being on and off will always be in 10rt intervals
Cuz of the checks being every 10rt
So it maybe be on for 10rt, 20, 30, 40 etc
So if u chain that pressure plate with another, the other will have the check also at 10rt intervals. And the first deactivates also at 10rt intervals. So it will always deactivate at the same moment of the check
Like always 5rt before the check

By Instructor Snow
